### Definition
- Seizure that lasts >= 5  min
- Or rapid successive seizures without full post-ictal recovery
- Increased risk of neuronal injury
- Duration
	- GTCS: >= 5min
	- Focal seizures with impaired consciousness: >= 10 min
	- [[Childhood absence epilepsy]]: 10-15 min

### Etiology: same as seizures, epilepsy, altered sensorium
- Antiepileptic Drug withdrawal
- Electrolyte: [[Hyponatremia]], [[Hypocalcemia]] 
- metabolic disturbances: [[Hypoglycemia]], [[Uremia]], [[Porphyrias]] 
- Structural brain lesions
- [[Hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy]], Anoxia
- [[Alcohol withdrawal]]
- Drugs: [[Tricyclic antidepressants]], [[Isoniazid]], recreational drugs 
- Infections: [[Cerebral malaria]], [[Encephalitis]], [[Prion diseases]]
- Late stage of [[Alzheimer disease]] 

### Management
- [[Primary survey]]: ABCDE management 
- [[Management.png]] algorithm 
- Summary
	1. Benzodiazepines at 1st 5-20 min
	2. Antiepileptic drugs at 20-40 min
	3. Inducing agent at >40 (refractory S.E.)
- Seizure crosses 5 min mark: [[Benzodiazepines]] every 5-10 min 
	- **Lorazepam 4 mg IV** at a maximum rate of 2 mg/minute; may repeat at three to five minutes if the seizure continues
	- **Midazolam 10 mg IM** if IV route not available
- Seizure not controlled for 20 min: [[Anti-Epileptic therapy]] 
	- 
- Seizure not controlled for 40 min: [[General Anesthetics]]
